16
$$$
One immediately recognizes "Young Adult" as a Diablo Cody script. This film belongs to her more than to Reitman. And that's a dual-edged sword.

"Young Adult" deals in trailer park sentiments (although Mavis' family is Midwestern middle class) played in an ugly urban landscape of dive bars and 'Kentacohuts'. Our recently divorced, depressed heroine hatches a plot to travel from Minneapolis (Cody's onetime residence) to her hometown, the fictional Mercury, Minnesota, to steal a happily married man (her hot, former HS sweetheart) from his wonderful wife. The couple's bliss is complete in their new child.

Her 'Sounding Board' (a Screen writing 101 plot element usually played by a same sex friend) is Oswalt. In HS he idolized Prom Queen Mavis (who ignored him), and was the victim of a nasty hate crime when Jocks, believing he's gay, pummel him with a crowbar.

Mavis holds the delusion her former flame (Wilson) is bored with small town domestic tranquility, and relentlessly pursues him until a spontaneous driveway intervention at the film's climax wakes her up. Kinda.

One edge of the aforementioned sword is that it's hard to like this film. Mavis, as written by Cody, has the appeal of a big bite on aluminum foil. Sadly, Mavis is drawn like the trailer park dwellers daily marched out by Springer. Theron plays the alcoholic, neurotic Mavis to perfection, but at the end she's still unlikable (even after a tender moment with Oswalt) as she drives back to 'Minneapple'.

Cody occasionally writes by stealth. In interviews, she's admitted to eavesdropping on and transcribing teen's conversations. As a writer of books for young adults, Mavis does as well. Such an obvious alter-ego crosses the fourth wall and is reason enough to dislike this film.

Cody's scripts are tight and well written yet paint-by-numbers in their tight grasp on American screen writing conventions.(Fairly, most Hollywood dreck uses the identical playbook.) The I'm-in-my-Thirties-but-still-cool-as-a-teen vibe is also an embarrassment.

There is something to be said for Cody's meditation on revisiting ancient regrets, grief and irrational jealousy. Many women might relate to the pain expressed in Mavis' barren womb (she miscarried Wilson's child during HS). This is the sword's other edge, but it's dull compared to the cut of the biting snark and unappealing lead character. Women should bristle at the portrayal of their gender in this slight twist of Cody's familiar coming of age stories. 

Cody shows contempt for the small town life she writes about. That makes "Young Adult" unpalatable and shifts viewer empathy to the self-loathing writer from where it belongs: story and character. Watch 'Juno" again.
