$$$
Young Adult (2011)

Well, Charlize Theron is a terrific actress. That makes this enough to sit through, regardless of the dull overlay this whole thing has. It's meant to be a gritty look at a woman with some mild mental problems, a not so mild alcohol problem, and a failing career. Oh, and a fetish for a previous lover who has since moved on and had a child and a wife.

That's the main point of the plot--Theron's character is determined to win back this man, despite a million reasons she simply can't. Well, don't tell her that. A third major character has some presence and might actually save the movie (along with Theron), and that's a supposedly unattractive man (played by Patton Oswalt) who is a thorn and a conscience for Theron. It works. The overall sense is a woman outside her boundaries and a man, this old friend from high school, who is still suffering from an experience as a teenager.

If only the writing rose to the occasion. There are awkward lines of dialog, improbable turns of events, extended dramatic scenes that would certainly play out differently than they do, and actors (the husband mainly) who just isn't believable (he can't be that naive). The director, Jason Reitman is clearly talented--his "Juno" is a kind of masterpiece, for sure, and even "Up in the Air" has a nice feel to it. This one has potential but clunks along too often to make sense.

You might forgive the whole thing if there was a feeling of insight into this kind of malaise, about loneliness or substance abuse or even an obsession with someone you can't have, but it turns into twists and reactions that are made from movies and fiction, not from life. Or so it felt.
